posts.body:
>>db5d47c0-9fc9-4a2e-aa7a-5b2aeac422dc
The only VPN worth jack shit is the one you made on your own server. Don't even bother with "no logs we swear 90% off if you bring 200 friends" crap.
Wrap your Tor around an obfs or meek bridge from bridges.torproject.org
99% undetectable from ISP side (and that's the only concern for a Tor user - not to give up to their ISP they're using Tor), even China can't do shit about it (other than throttle it like they throttle all outbound connections).
Don't waste your money.

>>f40ea3c7-af2f-4a8d-83e6-d55cd7df4cf3
>Just as safe, really
Not really.
Tor Browser is a Firefox fork specifically tweaked not to leak too much outside. That's why it's recommended for ZeroNet and generally it's not a bad idea to use it casually without Tor plugin as your default browser.
At least use Firefox, preferably with ghacks user.js. I certainly wouldn't recommend using anything Chrome with ZeroNet, because Google will definitely know you're using ZeroNet.

>>a0ce9f0c-1f0f-4f6a-9ea1-f276a5e2db56
>The journos are aleady lurking here
So they're literally helping Nazis with their bandwidth while they're looking.
Blue checkmarks are already dispatched to your house, Mr. Leibowitz.

>>25e3ad90-5dc4-4d91-9eec-be00bd51a4bb
You're missing other things. For example, Chrome can send data you enter in the address bar for Google SafeBrowsing, don't you thing it would be evident enough where you are if you enter http://127.0.0.1:43110/1DdP/?:users/1jsdjfierjrer:cp:0 ?

>>3c2b7f17-b314-4f4d-a8e3-fd0d9c9086dc
Commercial VPNs are shit.
If you want to hide your Tor from ISP, set a bridge.

>>81cd5096-ec5b-49e2-86df-a42a24958f96
Not necessary. You can interact with open port peers freely. You can't connect directly to closed port peers. So far with 1200 peers it shouldn't be a problem.
